    "what_description": "Rhodiola humilis is a perennial plant species belonging to the family Crassulaceae, native to mountainous regions of the Himalayas and the Tibetan Plateau. It has a compact, bushy habit with multiple stems, and its leaves are small, oval-shaped, and covered with fine hairs. The plant produces small, white or pale yellow flowers in late summer, which are arranged in clusters at the ends of the stems. Rhodiola humilis grows up to 20 cm in height and 30 cm in width, and its rhizomes are edible and used as a local food source. The plant's stems and leaves contain organic compounds, including rosmarinic acid and ursolic acid, which have been found to possess anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties.",
